Patch Set 5:

why are you implementing this as a plugin to the cherry-pick-bot? there is no apparent semantic overlap at all. in as far as code overlap exists (which i presume is the case for the gerrit access functions), extracting it to a proper library that can be used by both bots would seem like the proper engineering practice.

on the ui side, it seems weird to ask the users to enter the api password, something most users don't even have yet. it's also questionable from a security POV to "pipe" each user's password through a 3rd party hosted service. the state-of-the-art approach to such matters would be integrating with the qt account service through oauth (there would be still a single service account in the background that would do the gerrit group membership query, but that's ok).

on a more general note, i'm not quite sure that building a home-grown solution is even remotely economical. all you need is an authorization backend for one of the oodles of existing voting systems, and i wouldn't be _too_ surprised if someone already wrote a gerrit-based one. but as you already spent the time, that's a fairly moot point now anyway ... unless it turns out that the "minor polish" still required is actually the bulk of the work, as it has just about every single time the trolls decided to build something own from scratch. but whatever, not my business. have fun!

Patch Set 5:

> Patch Set 5:
> 
> why are you implementing this as a plugin to the cherry-pick-bot? 

Simply that I wanted to spin this up quickly, and cherry-pick-bot is already running and creating a plugin to serve a webpage and do some database operations was trivial. Ultimately, cherry-pick-bot is intended to host various bot plugins to do other functions, and there's not really any reason to not use it for this.

> on the ui side, it seems weird to ask the users to enter the api password, something most users don't even have yet. it's also questionable from a security POV to "pipe" each user's password through a 3rd party hosted service. the state-of-the-art approach to such matters would be integrating with the qt account service through oauth (there would be still a single service account in the background that would do the gerrit group membership query, but that's ok).

Agreed. I threw this together very quickly on-demand, and integrating with SSO isn't exactly trivial, and would require authorization to do so and some days spin-up time from the infrastructure owners. Using the API key was the easiest way and should be secure enough for now, implementing SSO if this tool gets developed as a more permanent solution. As the API password isn't known to most users, it shouldn't be disruptive to generate one, use it for voting, and then generate another to wipe the first one. I'll update the help message in the webform to give this recommendation.

> on a more general note, i'm not quite sure that building a home-grown solution is even remotely economical. all you need is an authorization backend for one of the oodles of existing voting systems, and i wouldn't be _too_ surprised if someone already wrote a gerrit-based one. but as you already spent the time, that's a fairly moot point now anyway ... unless it turns out that the "minor polish" still required is actually the bulk of the work, as it has just about every single time the trolls decided to build something own from scratch. but whatever, not my business. have fun!

Time spent: ~6 hrs, and I did search around and couldn't find anything gerrit-related for a voting system of any kind. I put this together as a stop-gap since no other obvious, reasonably secure system was available to fit our needs. The minor polish is a few if clauses in the code that will be completed today.
